-- WP10 (docs/spec/WASM-SEMANTICS.md §1) — #553 Stage A: the THIRD silent S0, and the one
-- nobody had ever named. It was found by the design pass, not by any gate or any report.
--
-- Like `eager_global_string_slice.mdk` and unlike `eager_global_call_hidden.mdk`, this
-- involves NO CALL — so WP10's stated remedy ("a closure that follows calls") leaves it
-- live. A match GUARD is evaluated EAGERLY when the arm is tested, so a global it reads is
-- a real init-order edge:
--
--   cell =
--     match 3
--       m if m < lim => "under"   -- `lim` is read here, at init time
--       _ => "over"
--   lim = 10                      -- ...but declared later
--
-- `eagerVarsArms` (compiler/backend/emit_support.mdk) matched `CArm pat _ body` — the
-- underscore DISCARDED THE ENTIRE GUARD LIST. So `lim` produced no edge, `cell` was
-- emitted before it, the guard compared against a still-zero cell, `3 < 0` was False, and
-- the program silently took the WRONG ARM.
--
-- Measured on the shipping engines BEFORE the fix (2026-07-17, origin/main 01eadd60):
--   eval   -> under          (correct)
--   native -> over, exit 0   (a WRONG ANSWER with no diagnostic — the S0)
--
-- Note the failure is not a null read or a crash: it is a wrong BRANCH. The poisoned zero
-- is a perfectly valid Int, the comparison succeeds, and the program returns a plausible
-- answer. There is nothing for a crash-based or trap-based gate to catch, on either
-- backend — which is why this one survived unnamed while the loud wasm arm of the same
-- root cause (#543) got noticed within a day.
--
-- Stage A replaced the discarding wildcard with `eagerVarsGuarded`, which walks the guard
-- chain and threads each `Pat <- e` guard's bindings into the guards to its right and the
-- body — matching the arm's real scoping rather than scanning flat.

cell =
  match 3
    m if m < lim => "under"
    _ => "over"

lim = 10

main = cell
